   <front>
      <title abbrev="XML Patch">A Media Type for XML Patch Operations</title>
      <author initials="E." surname="Wilde" fullname="Erik Wilde">
         <organization>EMC</organization>
         <address>
            <email>erik.wilde@emc.com</email>
         </address>
      </author>
      <author initials="M." surname="Nottingham" fullname="Mark Nottingham">
         <organization>Akamai</organization>
         <address>
            <email>mnot@mnot.net</email>
         </address>
      </author>
      <author initials="N." surname="Walsh" fullname="Norm Walsh">
         <organization>MarkLogic</organization>
         <address>
            <email>ndw@nwalsh.com</email>
         </address>
      </author>
      <date day="30" month="September" year="2012"/>
      <abstract>
         <t>The XML Patch media type "application/xml-patch" defines an XML document structure for expressing a sequence of operations to apply to an XML document. The XML Patch document format is defined in RFC 5261, this specification simply is a media type registration, so that XML Patch documents can be labeled with a media type, for example in HTTP conversations.</t>
      </abstract>
      <note title="Note to Readers">
         <t>This draft should be discussed on the <eref target="https://www.ietf.org/mailman/listinfo/apps-discuss">apps-discuss mailing list</eref>.</t>
         <t>Online access to all versions and files is available at <eref target="https://github.com/dret/I-D/tree/master/xml-patch">github</eref>.</t>
      </note>
   </front>
